@RaylenDavis When I recognize this mental model and how it plays itself out, I can counter with a more healthy and truthful thought process. What we are calling imposter syndrome, is most likely performance anxiety, we just didn’t have the knowledge yet.

@RaylenDavis It can be taught through our parents, siblings, or some significant care taker.  So for example, my dad fixated on his mistakes and never believed he was good enough. It was modeled to me and it helped form this core belief that this behavior is normal. It isn’t.

@RaylenDavis Performance anxiety is a core belief system we learn as a kid. It says “I am not good enough” it manifests with a “run or avoid”, a “counterattack”, and an “overcompensate” mentality. This is not a syndrome, but a mental model created very young.
Performance anxiety. It is at the root of imposter syndrome.
